		<img width="2400" height="1153" src="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-norway-eiders.jpg" class="singlepostthumb wp-post-image" alt="eider ducks" decoding="async" fetchpriority="high" srcset="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-norway-eiders.jpg 2400w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-norway-eiders-520x250.jpg 520w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-norway-eiders-1200x577.jpg 1200w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-norway-eiders-768x369.jpg 768w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-norway-eiders-1536x738.jpg 1536w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-norway-eiders-2048x984.jpg 2048w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-norway-eiders-900x432.jpg 900w" sizes="(max-width: 2400px) 100vw, 2400px" /><div class="post-thumbnail-caption">Eider ducks bob along a small fishing harbor in Straumen, Trøndelag, Norway. The ducks travel to Norwegian islands each spring, seeking a place to lay eggs and brood, and leaving behind valuable down. Photo by Pål Hermansen</div>
			<article class="main container col4">
								<header class="maincol">
										<h1 class="pagetitle">The Eider Keepers</h1>
										<h2 class="dek singlepagecontainer">An age-old tradition in Norway illuminates the bonds between wild ducks, wild places, and the people who care for both.</h2>
										<section class="singlebyline singlepagecontainer">
						<h3 class="invis">Authored by</h3>
						Text by Devon Fredericksen 								<br/>
							Photos by Pål Hermansen 								<br/>
												</section>
					 
					<aside class="singlebydatewords singlepagecontainer">
						<h3 class="invis">Wordcount</h3>
						March 21, 2024 | 3,700 words, about 19 minutes					</aside>
				</header>

